1585 1409 501 (. It is clear that C++ \(like C\)) 501 SB
396 1467 1560 (needs a standard library. The reason for this is that the language itself has no method for) 1560 SB
396 1525 1751 (communication with the system \(I/O, date/time and other system dependencies\). A standard library) 1751 SB
396 1583 1791 (for these system-dependent features is necessary to allow portable code to be written. The C standard) 1791 SB
396 1641 1783 (was focussed upon these issues, however the proposed C++ standard library introduces many classes) 1783 SB
396 1699 1753 (and features \(in particular standard data structures and algorithms\) that do not add to the portability) 1753 SB
396 1757 284 (of the language.) 284 SB
396 1841 1796 (This is not to say that it would not be nice to have standard definitions for these features, but it should) 1796 SB
396 1899 1715 (not be part of the C++ language standard. Adding these features to the C++ standard complicates) 1715 SB
396 1957 1775 (both the implementation \(e.g. for embedded systems\) and the learning of the language. Furthermore,) 1775 SB
396 2015 1776 (it is not clear at the moment whether the features included in the library are really what is needed. In) 1776 SB
396 2073 1700 (fact, if one considers the currently available commercial libraries as an indication, there is much) 1700 SB
396 2131 1792 (more need for a standard library for handling GUI\222s. This is understandable, since GUI interfaces are) 1792 SB
396 2189 1734 (generally system dependent and a standard library for that would greatly improve portability. This) 1734 SB
396 2247 1706 (cannot be said about e.g. a list data structure. A telling sign about the need for the features of the) 1706 SB
396 2305 1556 (current library is that currently it is not supported by any of the major C++ development) 1556 SB
396 2363 251 (environments.) 251 SB
